WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:17.000
We just went through an overview of software testing and assessments.

00:17.000 --> 00:20.000
Let's now get into some of the testing that we can actually perform.

00:31.000 --> 00:36.000
We just went through an overview of software testing and assessments.

00:36.000 --> 00:42.000
Let's now get into some of the testing that we can actually perform, some of the specific types of tests.

00:42.000 --> 00:48.000
Before we do that, actually, let's understand where could security be involved in testing.

00:48.000 --> 00:52.000
Now, this next diagram, do not memorize it for the exam.

00:52.000 --> 00:54.000
This is just Rob made this diagram up.

00:54.000 --> 00:57.000
But I find it helpful to visualize where you can do different types of testing

00:58.000 --> 01:00.000
and say the software development lifecycle.

01:00.000 --> 01:04.000
And so if we think about, say, the planning phase should security be involved in planning?

01:04.000 --> 01:09.000
Absolutely. Security can be involved to help make sure that the requirements have been appropriately captured,

01:09.000 --> 01:16.000
that all the security requirements that you need to be built into the system have been appropriately captured and validated.

01:16.000 --> 01:21.000
Next, design. Security can be heavily involved in designing what sort of control should be built into the system

01:21.000 --> 01:25.000
to provide confidentiality, integrity, availability, and so forth.

01:26.000 --> 01:31.000
Security can be involved in the actual development phase to make sure that those controls are actually being built into the system

01:31.000 --> 01:37.000
by performing things like vulnerability assessments and getting into things like unit, integration, and system testing

01:37.000 --> 01:39.000
that we'll talk about in a moment here.

01:39.000 --> 01:48.000
And security can be involved in the deployment process where the application is moved from QA into test into actual production.

01:48.000 --> 01:54.000
And security can be involved in doing things like vulnerability assessments and log analysis and so forth.

01:54.000 --> 02:00.000
And then finally, operation. When the system is actually out and being an operating system, security can continue to be involved in testing

02:00.000 --> 02:04.000
to continue to do validation, vulnerability assessment testing, log analysis.

02:04.000 --> 02:08.000
And there's even a part on here I haven't added, which would be what about when you decommission the system?

02:08.000 --> 02:13.000
Security can be involved then as well to make sure the data is securely destroyed and so forth.

02:13.000 --> 02:16.000
So security can be involved throughout all of this process.

02:16.000 --> 02:21.000
If you ever get a question asking you when, at what stage should security be coming involved?

02:21.000 --> 02:27.000
There's a very simple answer and that is the earliest possible stage on that list.

02:27.000 --> 02:35.000
If you see the dawn of time as one of the answers, that's probably the right answer because security should be involved from a start and throughout.

02:35.000 --> 02:42.000
This is why we have this concept of baking security in because security should be involved right from the start and throughout.

02:42.000 --> 02:46.000
And we so we refer to this as baking security into the system.

02:46.000 --> 02:50.000
Let's now look at some of the actual types of tests that we can do.

02:50.000 --> 02:53.000
The first is unit testing.

02:53.000 --> 02:56.000
Think about this way. Think of the Windows operating system.

02:56.000 --> 03:01.000
Windows is 50 million lines of code. It's a huge, huge piece of software.

03:01.000 --> 03:08.000
And there is not just one poor soul change to his chain to his desk or her desk in the basement of Microsoft that's been churning out the windows.

03:08.000 --> 03:11.000
There was 50 million lines of code for the past 20 years.

03:11.000 --> 03:14.000
No, there's many people that are changing to their desks doing that.

03:14.000 --> 03:21.000
The point is a huge software project like that involves whole teams of different people and to wildly oversimplify this.

03:21.000 --> 03:24.000
One team might be responsible for keyboard input.

03:24.000 --> 03:29.000
Another might be involved for mouse input. Another might be involved with displaying the graphics on the screen.

03:29.000 --> 03:35.000
And all of these different pieces, these different units of software are going to have to work with each other.

03:35.000 --> 03:41.000
And they're going to have to be designed ahead of time to be able to eventually connect to interface and work together.

03:41.000 --> 03:47.000
But when you first start developing, when a team is first given the task of saying, hey, you work on the keyboard input,

03:47.000 --> 03:50.000
the very first type of testing you can do is unit testing.

03:50.000 --> 04:00.000
If this unit of software is meant to take input from the keyboard, then you can test that little unit in isolation and make sure it does what it's supposed to do by itself.

04:00.000 --> 04:02.000
That's unit testing.

04:02.000 --> 04:08.000
As more and more units start to be built, you can start to do what's known as interface testing.

04:08.000 --> 04:15.000
Interfaces are standardized to find ways that these units are meant to connect to each other, talk with each other.

04:15.000 --> 04:20.000
And so interface testing is where you connect these pieces together and make sure they connect correctly.

04:20.000 --> 04:23.000
That's why I've included a graphics of some Lego blocks here.

04:23.000 --> 04:29.000
Because, you can buy Lego blocks today that will still work with Lego blocks made in the 1950s.

04:29.000 --> 04:37.000
And the reason they still work connect together properly is because it's a very precisely defined and controlled interface that is the Lego block.

04:37.000 --> 04:40.000
Same idea in software interface testing.

04:40.000 --> 04:44.000
You can make sure that these interfaces that are meant to connect to each other do.

04:44.000 --> 04:53.000
As you connect more and more of these units together, you can start to do integration testing, testing units, groups of units of software together.

04:53.000 --> 04:59.000
And as you build up and do more and more integration testing, you'll eventually get to the point where you can do system testing.

05:00.000 --> 05:08.000
This is where you can test the entire system with all of the units of software integrated together and working as one whole system testing.

05:08.000 --> 05:16.000
Now this final slide here, I've already talked about it, but I just love Lego and I figured out how to weigh it away to animate it so that the Lego blocks actually connect together.

05:16.000 --> 05:20.000
Yeah, there it is. So, that's the only takeaway from that slide. It's just interface testing.

